ce:section.ce:para:
The phosphorescent CDs@heme with photo-induced enzyme-like activity was prepared through a rapid microwave method (750 W, 5 min) using DAMO as the silicon source and H3PO4, KI and heme as raw materials (Scheme 1
                        ). Kang et al. showed that P atoms can be used as electron acceptors to modify the phosphorescence properties of CDs [29]. Therefore, we introduced P elements in the synthesis of CDs@heme to enhance the phosphorescence emission lifetime of the prepared CDs@heme. To enhance the RTP property of the prepared CDs@heme, four halides (NaF, NaCl, KBr, and KI) were used to explore their impacts on the RTP performance. As shown in Fig. 1
                        a, in the presence of iodine, the phosphorescence lifetime of CDs@heme has been effectively prolonged, which might be attributed to the strong interaction between the spin angular momentum and orbital angular momentum of the material molecules caused by the high nuclear electrons in halogen atoms, leading to the enhanced coupling of spin orbitals, the promotion of intersystem crossover (ISC) from singlet to triplet excitons, and finally the stronger phosphorescence emission [30]. Moreover, the intermolecular heavy-atom effect enhanced by halogen bonding considerably promotes the spin-orbit coupling (SOC) [31]. Furthermore, Kleinschmidt et al. showed that there exists competitive relation between ISC and the rates of phosphorescence radiative decay as well as other non-radiative decay processes, such as thermal deactivation and internal conversion [32]. If ISC rate speeds up and other non-radiative decay pathways (like vibrational dissipation or quenching) are effectively suppressed, the triplet excitons can more stably stay in the triplet energy level, leading to the prolonged phosphorescence lifetime. This stabilization process makes more excitons enter the triplet state via ISC through the enhanced SOC effect, and reduces non-radiative decay such as vibrational dissipation. Kleinschmidt's study also pointed out that the geometric structure differences between the triplet state and the ground state lead to lower non-radiative conversion efficiency, resulting in a decreased rate of phosphorescence decay [32].
